Boosting for regression trees

Lets start by simulating some data 

boost_simdat <- simulater(
  sequ = "x2 0 100", 
  grid = "x1 0 6.5 0.1", 
  form = "y = 10 + x1 * cos(pi * x1) - 0.1 * x2", 
  seed = 1234
)
summary(boost_simdat, dec = 4)

register("boost_simdat")
visualize(
  boost_simdat, 
  xvar = "x1", 
  yvar = "y", 
  type = "scatter", 
  nrobs = -1, 
  ylim = c(-5, 10),
  custom = TRUE
) +
  geom_line(data = boost_simdat, aes(x = x1, y = y), color = "blue")

Building a first (small) tree will, of course, not yield very accurate predictions. Add the predictions to the data set as pred_tree1

result <- crtree(
  boost_simdat, 
  rvar = "y", 
  evar = "x1", 
  type = "regression", 
  cp = 0.1
)
summary(result, prn = TRUE)

Now take the residuals from the first tree you estimated and use resid_tree1 as the response variable to build a new tree. Generate predictions for this tree and add them to the data set as pred_tree2

result <- crtree(
  boost_simdat, 
  rvar = "resid_tree1", 
  evar = "x1", 
  type = "regression", 
  cp = 0.1
)

Now take the residuals from the second tree you estimated and use resid_tree2 as the response variable to build a new tree. Generate predictions for this tree and add them to the data set as pred_tree3

The final prediction, assuming a learning rate of 1, is simply the sum of the predictions from the three trees we estimated.

boost_simdat <- mutate(
  boost_simdat,
  prediction = pred_tree1 + pred_tree2 + pred_tree3
)

visualize(
  boost_simdat, 
  xvar = "x1", 
  yvar = "prediction", 
  type = "line", 
  ylim = c(-5, 10),
  labs = list(y = "y"),
  linecol = "blue",
  custom = TRUE
) +
  geom_point(data = boost_simdat, aes(x = x1, y = y), alpha = 0.5)

Learning rates are generally set well below 1 in practice, but, as you can tell from the plot below that would require building many more trees to get a good fit to the data. The upside of a smaller learning rate is that we are less likely to overfit

boost_simdat <- mutate(
  boost_simdat,
  prediction = pred_tree1 + 0.1 * pred_tree2 + 0.1 * pred_tree3
)

visualize(
  boost_simdat, 
  xvar = "x1", 
  yvar = "prediction", 
  type = "line", 
  ylim = c(-5, 10),
  labs = list(y = "y"),
  linecol = "blue",
  custom = TRUE
) +
  geom_point(data = boost_simdat, aes(x = x1, y = y), alpha = 0.5)

Can XGBoost capture this patter well?

result <- gbt(
  boost_simdat, 
  rvar = "y", 
  evar = "x1", 
  type = "regression", 
  early_stopping_rounds = 3, 
  seed = 1234
)
summary(result, prn = TRUE)
